00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:15.600
It's really wonderful.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:20.530
So tonight we're going to focus
on this wonderful collaboration

00:04:20.530 --> 00:04:24.390
between Martha Graham and
Isamu Noguchi, and especially

00:04:24.390 --> 00:04:27.780
on one particular work,
"Cave of the Heart".

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:32.060
I'm here to speak from the Graham
side of the aisle because I danced

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:36.870
"Cave of the Heart" for many
years as the chorus and it was one

00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:38.850
of my very favorite roles.

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:42.120
Tonight I want to begin
to look at talking

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:45.580
about their common
aesthetic, the commonality

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:49.940
between these two artists and the
evolution of their discoveries,

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:53.050
their innovations for the stage
leading up to "Cave of the Heart"

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:58.330
so we can all better appreciate
what all is poured into this work

00:04:58.330 --> 00:05:04.650
that they arrived at in 1946, and
then I hope we'll have some time

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:08.500
for questions and perhaps
a social media moment.

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:11.180
We'll hope you'll take some
pictures of the set and Tweet them

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.070
or Instagram them, or
whatever you want to do.

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:18.300
So Martha and Noguchi had a
partnership, as Anne said,

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:23.560
that lasted for decades, created
over 20 unique works for the stage.

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:26.990
And though they were working
in different art forms,

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:32.560 position:56%
they were both searching for the
elemental shape, whether in movement

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:36.400
or in sculpture, that would
provide the viewer with what they

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:39.020
like to say the shock
of recognition,

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:43.000
a phrase that they borrowed from
their friend Buckminster Fuller.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.340
Noguchi said I wanted
something that was irreducible.

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:55.280
And Martha often said I
was after the thing itself.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:00.320
For Martha that involved creating
a revolutionary new type of dancing

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:05.580
that was borne out of natural
gesture, out of body language,

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:08.890
and while she was doing this,
Noguchi was experimenting

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:12.560
with the same idea,
the power of organic,

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:16.080
primal shapes in his sculptures.

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:19.820
Martha said she was attracted to
Noguchi's ideas because, quote,

00:06:19.820 --> 00:06:23.480
He had the astringency that
everything was stripped

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:26.580
to essentials, rather
than being decorative.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:28.460
Everything he does means something.

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:32.430
It is not abstract, except
if you think of orange juice

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:35.290
as the abstraction of an orange.

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:38.200
And that pretty much
describes her own aesthetics

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:43.950
to a T. I can't tell you how many
times in rehearsal she would stop

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:49.590
and rail against some lovely
new interpretation we had added

00:06:49.590 --> 00:06:53.040 position:56%
by saying it was frankly decorative.

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:56.300
That was the ultimate insult.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:01.910
Their first work for the
stage came about in 1935.

00:07:01.910 --> 00:07:06.320
I'm going to see if I
know how to do this now.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:11.310
Yes. Earlier in her career Martha
had rejected the traditional stage

00:07:11.310 --> 00:07:14.630
dÃ©cor, which was usually
a painted backdrop.

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:18.120
She considered it to be
distracting and decorative.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:22.070
And she danced on a bare
stage needing nothing else.

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:26.550
But as her work matured
she wanted the audience

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:31.750
to have more information and she
wanted a sense of place, location

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:36.670
and atmosphere, so she turned
to her friend Isamu Noguchi.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:43.120 position:56%
He had created a bust of her several
years earlier, which she hated,

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:48.640
and she insisted that he create
another, but they remained friends.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:52.400
And he created this set for
the solo she was working

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.700
on titled "Frontier."

00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:58.680
Noguchi later wrote about this set.

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:01.480
"Frontier" was my first set.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:05.530
It was, for me, the genesis of
an idea to wed the total void

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:09.170
of theater space to form an action.

00:08:09.170 --> 00:08:12.470
A rope running from the two
top corners of the proscenium

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:14.990
to the floor rear center
of the stage,

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:19.320
bisected the three
dimensional void of stage space.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:22.330
This seemed to throw the
entire volume of air straight

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:24.900
out over the heads of the audience.

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:28.690
At the rear convergence there
was a small section of log fence

00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:31.440
to start from and return to.

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:37.130 position:56%
The white ropes created a curious
ennobling of an outburst into space,

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:42.730
and at the same time, of the
public's inrush towards infinity.

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:46.310
Martha had suggested to him
that she wanted something

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:48.050
like the railroad tracks.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:50.790
Her family traveled
across country quite often,

00:08:50.790 --> 00:08:54.260
and that idea of perspective.

00:08:54.260 --> 00:08:57.810
Noguchi finished, This set
was the point of departure

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:00.780
for all my subsequent theater work.

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:05.780
Space became a volume to
be dealt with sculpturally.

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:09.000
Prior to "Frontier" in 1935 --

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.950
there's one with Martha
next to the set --

00:09:11.950 --> 00:09:15.210
Martha had already been
experimenting with this idea

00:09:15.210 --> 00:09:19.850
of the power of manipulating
the empty space on stage

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:23.530
with her choreography for
large groups of women.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:32.440
"Heretic," from 1929, is a prime
example of Martha's use of space

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:36.230
to support her emotional
theme, with its wall of women

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:39.700
in black constantly shifting
and blocking the path,

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:43.280
blocking the freedom of
the lone figure in white.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:48.960
It was a modernist, geometric
evocation of oppression.

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:52.360
In her classics "Primitive
Mysteries" from 1931,

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:56.600
"Celebration" from '34,
and "Panorama" from 1935,

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:02.100 position:56%
which had a cast of 33 dancers,
Martha was mining the space on stage

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:06.610
with her geometric patterns,
the counterpoint of these groups

00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:12.610
of women, to create pathways,
tableaus, lines of force

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:14.300
and different levels

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:18.600
to most powerfully send her
message, her emotional message.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:22.580
In fact, "Panorama" used
ramps and staircases on stage,

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:26.510
as well as an overhead
mobile by Alexander Calder.

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:30.620
So she was primed with these ideas
when she and Noguchi connected,

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:38.120
and the two of them continued to
innovate and develop this idea.

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:42.140
You'll see "Appalachian Spring"
in our programs this weekend,

00:10:42.140 --> 00:10:45.010
and I'm going to show
you a little bit of it.

00:10:45.010 --> 00:10:52.690
The stage here at the Library
is concise, so we do --

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:58.530
part of the set is kind of through
the door in the back of the stage,

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:00.770
but that's the way
Martha must have done it

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:04.880
in the very first performance,
but I want to show you a film

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:09.590
that shows you the entire set and
you'll see that it's an extension

00:11:09.590 --> 00:11:13.490
of the discoveries Noguchi
talked about in "Frontier".

00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:19.400 position:56%
The beams of this house, this
outline of a house that is on stage,

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:23.090
have that same idea of
perspective built into them

00:11:23.090 --> 00:11:27.170
so that space is pushed out
over the audience's head,

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:29.840
and at the same time inviting them

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:34.300
in to this new home
nestled in the prairie.

00:11:34.300 --> 00:11:36.300
Let me see if I can manage this.

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:39.310
Come on. There it is.

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:42.810
This is kind of a side
view at the moment.

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:50.440
The camera's going to come around

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:54.510
and give you the front
and center view.

00:11:54.510 --> 00:12:30.040
[ Music ]

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:32.420
You might have caught a
bit of it in that clip,

00:12:32.420 --> 00:12:35.680
but you'll definitely see
it in performance this week,

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:40.980
that the dancers are also
required to inhabit this new space

00:12:40.980 --> 00:12:43.740
that Noguchi has created.

00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:48.600
So as they enter, and in many
places throughout the ballet,

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:53.980
they gesture out across the
limitless space, the frontier,

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:57.690
the future, they gaze
out in that direction.

00:12:57.690 --> 00:13:02.320
The pioneering woman is often
making sure that there's no trouble

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:05.870
out there, out on the prairie.

00:13:05.870 --> 00:13:10.720
So it's quite a revolutionary
aspect of what Graham

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:13.230
and Noguchi put together.

00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:17.720
Now, they no sooner had sort of
conquered this idea of extending

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:21.750
and changing the space on stage,
but they began to understand

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:26.820
that they could also evoke inner
space, the psychological space.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:30.000
As Martha liked to call
it, the inner landscape.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.960
And while she began
choreographing the mind,

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:39.620
Noguchi was using organic shape
to also evoke the interior.

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:44.580 position:56%
The same evening as they premiered
"Appalachian Spring" at the Library,

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:48.750
they premiered "Herodiade,"
with a score by Paul Hindemith,

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:50.580 position:56%
another commission from the Library.

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:52.930
It's kind of a mysterious dance,

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:55.120
even to those of us
who have danced it.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:57.320
There's no exact narrative.

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:01.930
This may be a woman choosing
between life and death,

00:14:01.930 --> 00:14:05.850
it may be a recurring
theme in Graham's work,

00:14:05.850 --> 00:14:09.930
the dilemma of the creative artist
fighting against repression,

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:14.920
but it's definitely an
internal battle made visible.

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:19.880
Noguchi said about his set that
"Herodiade" was the most Baroque

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:23.820
and specifically sculptural
of my sets.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:28.580
Within a woman's private world
and intimate space I was asked

00:14:28.580 --> 00:14:33.080
to place a mirror, a
chair and a clothes rack.

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:35.280
Salome dances before her mirror.

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:36.720
What does she see?

00:14:36.720 --> 00:14:40.790
Her bones, the potential
skeleton of her body.

00:14:40.790 --> 00:14:44.670
The chair is like an extension of
her vertebrae; the clothes rack,

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:48.660
the circumscribed bones
on which is hung her skin.

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:53.750
This is the desecration of
beauty, the consciousness of time.

00:14:53.750 --> 00:14:56.580
So the mirror is on
the left side there,

00:14:56.580 --> 00:15:00.890
with the swinging moon-shaped
articles,

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:08.030
and Martha in her solos would
advance to it and back away,

00:15:08.030 --> 00:15:10.280
really aiming for the bird.

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:14.260
She used to talk about the bird
in the center of the mirror

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:18.610
that was the animating
life that she could dance

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:23.060
to in the middle of this.

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:28.860
So following "Appalachian Spring"
and "Herodiade" in 1944 Graham

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:33.380
and Noguchi did three works
that I consider to be some

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:36.760
of their greatest, all
based on Greek myth.

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:41.550
They both were this was a common
to both of them, very interested

00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:44.970
in myth and legend,
and to the archaic,

00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:47.810
archaic art of ancient cultures.

00:15:47.810 --> 00:15:53.920
I think they understood that these
ancient stories were elemental

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:58.690 position:56%
to the human condition and very much
aligned with what they were trying

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:01.500
to do in their modernist form.

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:04.840
These three works;
"Errand into the Maze,"

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:07.960
"Cave of the Heart"
and "Night Journey".

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:16.080
Using the classics as inspiration
also gave Martha another advantage.

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:20.370
Again, the audience would
arrive with pre knowledge.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:22.980
They knew the characters
and she didn't have

00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:24.660
to spend any time introducing them.

00:16:24.660 --> 00:16:28.020 position:56%
She could dive right into the drama.

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:33.200
And so not satisfied with just
manipulating space on stage,

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:37.450
Martha was now also beginning
to rearrange time on stage,

00:16:37.450 --> 00:16:42.320 position:56%
choreographing memories,
flashbacks, stream of consciousness.

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:46.810
"Night Journey" from 1947
is probably the best example

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:48.290
of this technique.

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:51.470
It's Martha's version
of the Oedipus story,

00:16:51.470 --> 00:16:55.430
and it begins as Sophocles'
play ends,

00:16:55.430 --> 00:16:59.190
with Jocasta having discovered
the truth and the curtain goes

00:16:59.190 --> 00:17:04.370
up with her holding the rope over
her head and about to end her life.

00:17:04.370 --> 00:17:09.560
The ballet takes place, it's
about a 30 minute ballet,

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:12.520
as if her life flashes
before her eyes

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:14.810
in the seconds before
she does herself in.

00:17:14.810 --> 00:17:18.140
She remembers Oedipus and
she remembers their marriage

00:17:18.140 --> 00:17:20.860
and discovering the
truth, and the ballet ends

00:17:20.860 --> 00:17:25.280
with her tightening the rope around
her neck and doing herself in.

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:28.110
For this dance, this
story of incest --

00:17:28.110 --> 00:17:31.110
I'm going to have to shoot through.

00:17:31.110 --> 00:17:33.850
Sorry, you're going to see
"Errand into the Maze".

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:39.910
Noguchi created a bed, but it's
more than a bed, of course.

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:43.390
He said, I created a bed
as the central sculpture,

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:46.970
a double image of male and female.

00:17:46.970 --> 00:17:51.100
So you can see the left side
of the bed is the phallic side,

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:53.010
the male side, and the right side

00:17:53.010 --> 00:17:57.920
of the bed has the organic
breasts, if you will.

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:05.740
So his organic shapes, it was as
Noguchi could be so practical,

00:18:05.740 --> 00:18:10.370
it was a bed and a story
about incest, but it just has

00:18:10.370 --> 00:18:16.280
so many more meanings
in its beautiful shape.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:22.570 position:56%
I want to detour just a little while
we're talking about organic shape,

00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:27.750
to talk a little bit more
about Martha's interest in this

00:18:27.750 --> 00:18:30.800
because one could say, well,
you've got a body on the stage,

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:33.060
that's an organic shape, right.

00:18:33.060 --> 00:18:40.060
But really, Martha's technique is a
little more complicated than that.

00:18:40.060 --> 00:18:45.610
In the 1920s she was dissatisfied
with dance of the day, which was,

00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:50.380 position:56%
frankly, decorative, escapist, gods
and goddesses from imaginary places,

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:53.690
kings and queens, swans and
flowers, and that sort of thing,

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:55.790
and she really wanted to dance

00:18:55.790 --> 00:18:59.710
about real human emotions
and the human condition.

00:18:59.710 --> 00:19:06.690
And she started experimenting
with and studying body language,

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:12.760
how we hold ourselves when we are
under stress or when we're in love

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:19.660 position:56%
or when we laugh or when we cry,
and she discovered her new approach.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:23.650 position:56%
One of the things she discovered was
that emotion rides on the breath.

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:26.300
When you're nervous,
oh, it's on your breath.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:28.700
When you sob, when you
laugh, it's all coming

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:30.930
from the center of your torso.

00:19:30.930 --> 00:19:36.300
And through that idea she developed
her famous contraction and release;

00:19:36.300 --> 00:19:41.760
the contraction being the coiling
in, the folding of the torso,

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:46.090
[demonstrating], the exhale, and
the release being the inhale,

00:19:46.090 --> 00:19:47.390
[demonstrating], and the expansion

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:50.710
that sends energy throughout
the whole body.

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:57.160
I'm going to put on a video
and I'm going to keep talking.

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:01.950
This is an excerpt from a
Martha Graham classroom,

00:20:01.950 --> 00:20:07.640
from a technique class, and in a
Graham technique class we spend

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:11.290
about the first 30 minutes of
a 90 minute class on the floor,

00:20:11.290 --> 00:20:16.570
sitting on the floor, so that you
articulate and strengthen the torso

00:20:16.570 --> 00:20:19.330
without the legs getting involved.

00:20:19.330 --> 00:20:24.300
Of course, they are involved, but
and so you'll see in this exercise,

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:25.650
which probably the one you're

00:20:25.650 --> 00:20:28.910
about to see would happen
20 minutes into a class.

00:20:28.910 --> 00:20:32.480
We've gone through the basic
contractions and releases.

00:20:32.480 --> 00:20:39.060
Okay. It's going to
come up, isn't it?

00:20:40.610 --> 00:20:41.910
Give it a minute.

00:20:41.910 --> 00:20:44.350
There we go.

00:20:44.350 --> 00:20:46.460
And this one's a little
more complicated.

00:20:46.460 --> 00:20:53.100
You'll see the torso
is not only contracting

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:55.330
and releasing, but it's spiraling.

00:20:55.330 --> 00:20:58.810
The legs are leveraging
against the floor.

00:21:03.190 --> 00:21:09.150
And she began to understand, as
she developed this technique --

00:21:09.150 --> 00:21:11.910
and she developed it
on stage, really.

00:21:11.910 --> 00:21:15.040
She had a vision for what
she wanted on the stage,

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:18.410
and then began excerpting the
movement that she was putting

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:22.770
on the stage into the classroom
so that she could study it

00:21:22.770 --> 00:21:24.680
and teach it to other dancers.

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:27.880
So it's a very dramatic
emotional technique.

00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:33.210 position:56%
And she began to understand how
intimate and emotional, even erotic,

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:37.260
movement driven by the
torso and the pelvis can be.

00:21:37.260 --> 00:21:41.790
And at the same time she saw how
much physical power is generated

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:46.290
by using the core muscles, the
weight of the body leveraging

00:21:46.290 --> 00:21:50.270
against the earth, rather
than the antigravity goals

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:51.600
of classical ballet.

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:52.900
Quite the opposite.

00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:57.160
She wanted both the power
and the message of effort.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:05.420
These are called pleading
contractions,

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:09.270
and we're encouraged
to think of the Pieta.

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:14.540
We're showing the vulnerability
of the inner wrist and the side

00:22:14.540 --> 00:22:16.970
of the neck exposing the jugular.

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:27.530
Release.

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:45.780
Big contraction.

00:22:45.780 --> 00:22:51.370
So on our programs this
weekend all of the Graham works

00:22:51.370 --> 00:22:55.790
on these programs will
be using this vocabulary

00:22:55.790 --> 00:22:59.800
that is entirely driven
by the torso.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:05.030
It's not always a very obvious
big contraction and release.

00:23:05.030 --> 00:23:09.480
Sometimes it's a simple shift
of the back that makes us walk.

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:13.380
There's no such thing as just
sort of a casual Graham walk.

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:18.830 position:56%
It's the weight of the body
shifting before the foot catches it.

00:23:18.830 --> 00:23:23.850
In Medea's dance of vengeance,
her second solo, she begins --

00:23:23.850 --> 00:23:27.430
you'll think she's just standing
stock still and then you'll begin

00:23:27.430 --> 00:23:33.530
to see her dress vibrate and her
whole body is shaking with fury.

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:38.120
These are all little contractions,
stuff coming from the center

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:44.260
of her body to denote
these emotional things.

00:23:44.260 --> 00:23:50.820
They're going to do a
little bit more for us.

00:23:52.310 --> 00:23:54.460
There's a beautiful contraction.

00:23:54.460 --> 00:23:58.600
They're going to go
into a full another move

00:23:58.600 --> 00:24:05.380
from Medea is what we call the knee
vibrations, where her insides are

00:24:05.380 --> 00:24:12.500 position:56%
so stirred up that it gets the leg
involved, but again, it's all coming

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:17.950
from the torso, contracting
and releasing, and the turmoil

00:24:17.950 --> 00:24:23.920
in the what she's going through
shows throughout her whole body.

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:25.230
All right.

00:24:25.230 --> 00:24:27.970
I'll let them keep going for a
minute, but I want to now talk

00:24:27.970 --> 00:24:32.460
about the specifics, specifics
of "Cave of the Heart".

00:24:32.460 --> 00:24:37.370
Martha was so eager to
choreograph this story.

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:44.270
In 1941 she wrote a script
titled "Daughter of Colchis,"

00:24:44.270 --> 00:24:47.400
about the dance drama she
envisioned, and she wrote,

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:51.810
about Medea, To me, she
is a barbarian princess.

00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:55.950
She possesses the animality
of the undisciplined being.

00:24:55.950 --> 00:25:00.150
It is bitter, sardonic,
murderess, despairing.

00:25:00.150 --> 00:25:03.280
Someplace I read that it might
be any wife to any husband.

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:07.280
I ought to know about that.

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:12.730
She intended to do Medea as the
first commission with the Library

00:25:12.730 --> 00:25:18.090 position:56%
of Congress, and she sent that
script to Aaron Copland who declined

00:25:18.090 --> 00:25:24.760 position:56%
and suggested it might be nice, as
he said, to be a little less severe,

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:28.510
maybe a combination of "Our Town"
and the script that you sent me.

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:31.320
[ Laughter ]

00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:36.720
So in 1942 she sent the
script to Carlos Chavez,

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.410
but the score that Chavez sent her
did not have what she called the

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:44.350
secret violence that she
had described in the script

00:25:44.350 --> 00:25:47.640
and she decided the score
was without stage awareness,

00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:50.560
so she didn't use it
until a few years later,

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:54.150
when she created a gorgeous ballet,

00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:57.240
"Dark Meadow," from
the Chavez score.

00:25:57.240 --> 00:25:59.640
Very ritualistic.

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:03.190
It's known as her Jungian ballet.

00:26:03.190 --> 00:26:06.540
And we are doing highlights
from "Dark Meadow"

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:08.520
on our program this weekend.

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:14.820
So finally, in 1945, now we're four
years later, she sent the script

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:19.080
to Samuel Barber who created the
score that you'll hear with "Cave

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:24.330
of the Heart" today, and which
has become a well known standard

00:26:24.330 --> 00:26:27.380
orchestral work in the
American concert repertoire.

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:30.920
So "Cave of the Heart"
premiered in 1946.

00:26:30.920 --> 00:26:37.240
Martha, of course, stripped the
Greek tragedy down to its essences,

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:41.710
and Noguchi matched her
with the abstract set pieces

00:26:41.710 --> 00:26:45.840
that evoke both story
elements as well as some

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:48.230
of the most basic human emotions.

00:26:48.230 --> 00:26:52.840
The action in "Cave of the Heart"
is carried by four players only;

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:57.770
the sorceress Medea, who has
been rejected by her lover;

00:26:57.770 --> 00:27:01.360
the ambitious Jason,
who's overthrown Medea

00:27:01.360 --> 00:27:06.200
to make a political marriage to the
princess; the innocent princess,

00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:11.460
Jason's new bride; and the
all-knowing but powerless Chorus,

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:17.190
who warns the audience that a
tale of horror is about to unfold.

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:20.960
Now, about the set.

00:27:20.960 --> 00:27:24.450
It's both a landscape
and an inner landscape.

00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:27.190
Noguchi said, I constructed
a landscape

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:29.470
like the islands of Greece.

00:27:29.470 --> 00:27:33.260
On the horizon, center
rear, lies a volcanic shape

00:27:33.260 --> 00:27:36.660
like a black aorta, like a heart.

00:27:36.660 --> 00:27:39.880 position:56%
To this leads steppingstone islands.

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:44.080
This references Jason's
voyage and the Golden Fleece.

00:27:44.080 --> 00:27:46.710
Opposite is coiled a green serpent

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:51.220
on whose back rests the
transformational dress of gold.

00:27:52.990 --> 00:27:59.290
So these five smaller rocks are the
Greek Islands, the stepping stones.

00:27:59.290 --> 00:28:00.990
Of course, they're in a
different place on the stage.

00:28:00.990 --> 00:28:03.680
I think one of my video clips
will show you how they're set

00:28:03.680 --> 00:28:05.300
up on stage.

00:28:05.300 --> 00:28:11.160
And this is the serpent,
Medea's sort of home base,

00:28:11.160 --> 00:28:14.290
with the transformational
dress on top.

00:28:14.290 --> 00:28:17.410
Martha said, When I needed
a place for Medea on stage,

00:28:17.410 --> 00:28:22.080
the heart of her being,
Isamu brought me a snake.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:25.210
And Noguchi said, Martha
didn't ask me to make a snake.

00:28:25.210 --> 00:28:27.640
These are objects that
I make that derive

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:30.850
from a depiction of
an emotional state.

00:28:30.850 --> 00:28:33.350
So as Martha choreographed
she integrated this set

00:28:33.350 --> 00:28:34.870
into the choreography.

00:28:34.870 --> 00:28:37.350
Noguchi's design, of
course, gave her pathways

00:28:37.350 --> 00:28:40.480
and gave her different
levels and places to hide.

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:42.430
Each character has a home base.

00:28:42.430 --> 00:28:46.590
We have Medea's here with us, and
you'll see when she's on stage,

00:28:46.590 --> 00:28:51.170
you're viewing it from the
front and she is so low inside,

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:54.920
it's almost like there's a
lower level to the stage.

00:28:54.920 --> 00:28:56.930
It's almost as if she's
below the area.

00:28:56.930 --> 00:29:00.740
And she's hiding things
behind the serpent that appear

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:03.420
in the course of the dance.

00:29:03.420 --> 00:29:08.330
The chorus, her home base
is the heart, the aorta,

00:29:08.330 --> 00:29:11.300
which is not on display,
you'll see in one of the clips.

00:29:11.300 --> 00:29:14.620
And the dancers call it the
elephant because it looks

00:29:14.620 --> 00:29:16.260
like an elephant lying on its back

00:29:16.260 --> 00:29:19.280
with four feet sticking
up in the air.

00:29:19.280 --> 00:29:29.350 position:56%
And the great creativity in how
Martha has designed the choreography

00:29:29.350 --> 00:29:31.470
for the chorus and for
the other characters

00:29:31.470 --> 00:29:35.180
to use the different
levels and the ins and outs

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:38.310
of the elephant is quite wonderful.

00:29:38.310 --> 00:29:40.540
Who else. Jason.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:43.660
Jason's home base is really
the five Greek Islands

00:29:43.660 --> 00:29:47.250
that he strides across on occasion.

00:29:47.250 --> 00:29:54.470
At the pinnacle of his male
chauvinistic arrogance he takes the

00:29:54.470 --> 00:29:59.110
princess up onto the heart center
stage and puts her on one corner

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:04.280 position:56%
and straddles two other corners as
absolute the highest point on stage,

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:10.770
which Martha has used specifically
this high and mighty position

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:16.470
to prime us all for the great
fall that is about to happen.

00:30:16.470 --> 00:30:18.420
The princess' home base is Jason,

00:30:18.420 --> 00:30:21.040
